Charles W. Michael) argued that "everything connected with the lives of Black Swifts tends to hold the secret of their nesting activities"[25] .Birds are ready to breed in May - July in Costa Rica, in June - July in Dominica, mating behavior is observed from June to early August in southwestern Canada and the northwestern United States. Birds lay eggs in British Columbia from late June, in California - from mid-June to the end of July, in Costa Rica - at the end of May. Colonies with chicks were noted in the state of Veracruz in Mexico in July, in Colorado in the USA - in July - August, in Montana - at the end of July [2 ].